Questions

Scale up Language-labelled Robot Data Generation

In the first part, we **scale up** language-labelled robot data generation. This part starts off standard with a language model planner. It takes a task description and decomposes the task into simpler subtasks.
This is where other works might assume action primitives, which have high execution success rates. Instead, we will ground the plan into a set of sampling-based robot planners. These include grasp samplers, placement samplers, and motion planning.
By virtue of using sampling-based planners, we get rich manipulation skills that the LM can't do alone, while getting flexibility to novel tasks & domains.

High Entropy, Precise Actions


Here's a visualization of our policy in the drawer domain. These colorful lines that you see here are the action sequence predictions. Since our diffusion policy is capable of learning the diverse distribution of successful actions from sampling based planners, it can output high entropy actions when possible, and precise actions when necessary.

Distilled Common Sense


Here's another visualization of our policy in the catapult domain. It would be difficult to apply TAMP-based approaches here because it's difficult to plan through contact and dynamics. Instead, we use common-sense planning from language models, which is sufficient for exploration. This is not just a fun example of tool use, but also a demonstration why common-sense is ideal.

Data Generation Results

Looking at the data generation numbers, we start with a language-model planner that uses only top down pick and places with a fixed z orientation, and does not use verify & retry. In other words, the language model predicts a sequence of API calls over top down pick and places, then executes predicted actions in an open-loop fashion. This is similar to the Code-as-policy approach. Building on top of this baseline, if we instead give it API access to the same sampling-based planners our data generation approach has, success drops. Why is that?

Data Generation Results

Expanding the bar chart to all domains here, we see that for simple tasks indeed performance drops. However, this expressive action space is crucial for exploration in more complex tasks. For instance, the transport domain involves transporting a single object to a target bin, but the object has complex geometry which can't always be successfully grasped with a top down pick. Similarly, the mailbox and drawer domain has articulated joints. But notice how the mailbox domain, our longest horizon domain, still has zero success rates, even with the sampling-based planners, until we introduce verify & retry.

Data Generation Results

This underscores the importance of recovery after failure especially when performing challenging long horizon 6 DoF manipulation such as those required in the mailbox domain.
Questions

Data Generation Results

So, with the addition of verify & retry, the data collection policy has higher success rates. Quantitatively, if we want successful trajectories to learn from, we will get much higher efficiency with the latter.
Qualitatively, though, there is also an interesting difference.

Distilled Retrying Behavior

Here's a plot showing success rates by episode time as a function of how much time is given.
When our data generation policy's grasp or placement attempts fail, it detects this with its inferred success condition and retries. This means the more time you give it, the more successful it will be, giving this monotonically increasing line.
This does not just lead to higher success rates but also, crucially, *demonstrates* retrying behavior to the distilled policy. And indeed, we not only see that the distilled policy successfully inherits this behavior from its data, but also *improves upon* it thanks to success filtering.
In contrast, without verify & retry, the data collection policy achieves low success rates, halting after the first attempt. So, even when you take only the successful trajectories from such a data collection policy and distill out a policy, it inherits this brittle open-loop behavior.
Questions

Distilled Policy Results

Across all the domains we evaluated the policy on, training on data with retrying behavior helps significantly.
Further, even with the simple data processing strategy of success filtering, we already observe a doubling of performance from the data collection policy to the distilled policy.
Questions
Now, the learned policy's performance is a function of two things: 1) the data, and 2) the policy learning approach. We've just seen that data matters, but how much does the policy learning approach matter? It turns out quite a bit.
Here, we compare against BC-Zero, and varied all policy learning configurations including policy output design choices like action representation (absolute or delta), action sequence execution & prediction horizon, as well as policy output design choices.

The single most important design choice seems to be how the action is generated. BC-Zero policy's action generation is a feed forward multi-layer perceptron, trained with a huber loss. When learning from the diverse data generated from the sampling-based planners, it never achieved more than 35.5%.
Meanwhile, our policy's action generation is a pseudo-random diffusion process, trained with the denoising loss. This allows it to deal with high entropy, multi-modal data much better.
Questions

High Distilled Performance from Diverse Attempts

Verify & Retry
🚀 High data generation success rate
🔄 Retry after failure
+
Diverse Attempts
🎲 Sampling-based planners
🧠 Diffusion Policy
The upshot is this. If you want high performance for your visuo-motor policy, you will need two ingredients. First, with verify & retry, you not only increase data generation success rates, but also demonstrate retry after failure behaviors. But simply retrying alone is not sufficient if each attempt is identical to the previous one. Therefore, to ensure you have diverse attempts at data generation time, you can use sampling-based planners, and distill the resulting high-entropy robot data into a policy architecture, capable of learning from such multi-modal distributions.

Real-world Deployment With No Fine-tuning

Finally, when trained with visual domain randomization, our policy can directly transfer to the real-world without further finetuning.

A Framework for Scalable Skill Learning

So, today, I've told you about a unified framework for scalable robot skill learning.
In the data generation phase, the framework takes as input task descriptions, and for each of those tasks, uses a language model to plan over sampling-based robot planners. You can run this for as long as you want to generate a large multi-task robot dataset. This is how we scale up

A Framework for Scalable Skill Learning

language-labelled robot data generation.

A Framework for Scalable Skill Learning

In the policy training phase, we process the data by filtering for success, and train a language-conditioned visuo-motor diffusion policy.

A Framework for Scalable Skill Learning

which can solve common-sense tasks and exhibits rich 6 DoF manipulation capabilities. Further, since it does not rely on state information, it can be used directly for real world deployment.
I would like to zoom back out here, and remark that it is an especially exciting time to be working on AI and Robotics. This is because the ongoing rapid advancements in language models are enabling unprecedented levels of automation. As people try to apply language models to every aspect of life, we are beginning to see a recipe on how to use these language models emerge, for which Scaling Up & Distilling Down is one such instance. I will call the recipe the language-guided automation recipe.

The Language-guided Automation Recipe

The Language-guided Automation Recipe

Language Models
✅ high-level flexibility

guide

External Tools
✅ low-level heavy-lifting

Google Bard , Google Blog

OpenAI GPT-4 , Unite.AI

At the high level, the recipe pairs the language model with some external tool. Here, the language model interacts with the user and guides the tool in carrying out the user's intent. For instance, you can have language models translate your queries into prompts which works best with your image generation model, or write and directly run code to analyze stocks. The language model provides high-level flexibility thanks to its zero-shot common-sense abilities. Meanwhile, the tool handles the low-level heavy lifting that is not suitable to squeeze into the language-model's training. This is what I mean by language-guided.

The Language-guided Automation Recipe

Language models aren't directly outputting the final answers, but instead mediating between the user and the external tools, guiding the entire process. But why should us roboticists care about this?

A Robot Skill Learning Workflow

Well, let's think about some of the tasks us robot learning researchers might do when they are trying to learn new robot skills. We might set up the environment and tasks, collect the multi-task robot data, label them with task success/reward or task descriptions, then we train the visuo-motor policy.

A Robot Skill Learning Workflow

The first three stages is extremely manual labor intensive, potentially requiring many robots, human operators to collect tens of thousands of trajectories. In the case of SayCan, 68000 teleoperated demonstrations took 10 robots over 11 months.

A Robot Skill Learning Workflow

So the part of our robot learning pipeline can really benefit from automation is in the collection and labelling of this multi-task robot dataset. this is where its best to apply the language-guided automation recipe.
And I think some others in our field would also agree.

How we can put robotics on the same scaling trends as large language models while not compromising on robust manipulation and control?

All this is to say, I think we are ready to start thinking about how our robot policies can keep up with language model advancements. How we can put robotics on the same scaling trends as large language models while not compromising on robust manipulation and control? This framework is a step towards this direction. Future Work

Limitations

  1. Sim2Real. Online adaptation to novel visual & physical domains.
  2. Trajectory Generation. More embodiments and tasks.
  3. Asset/Environment Design. Procedural & learned approaches.

Opportunities

  1. Policy Scalability. A trade-off between inductive biases and expressivity.
  2. Data Investigation. Fix the algorithm, control data generation.

This work is not without limitations. I think there is still a lot to do on the Sim2Real front beyond domain randomization, which enables better online adaptation to novel domains visually as well as physically.
Further, what kind of robot tasks and embodiments we can support is determined by what external tools we give to the language model. On the trajectory generation front, maybe MPC is all we might need to extend this to more bipeds, quadrupeds, and dexterous, dynamic tasks.
After these two points, the last bottleneck of the system is in asset and environment design, for which both state-of-the-art procedural and learned approaches holds a lot of promise.
Personally, though, I'm extremely excited about what automatic robot data generation as a tool enables.
We can now ask questions regarding policy learning scalability. When Vision Transformers came out, it outperformed Convolutional Neural Networks. It turns out that the convolution inductive bias only helped in the low-data regime. So how much of the current state-of-the-art robot policy learning rankings now are an artifact of the low-data regime. Rather than hoping that our findings extrapolate to the high-data regime, we can now test it.
Lastly, with the opportunity to fully control our data generation process, we can gain a much better understanding of robot data. In this project, I've seen that just including retrying behavior helps performance significantly. If we fix the algorithm and dataset size, but include or remove some behaviors from the dataset, how does that affect downstream performance? In general, what makes good robot data?

Domain Randomization

Full Sim Results

When sampling-based planners are first introduced, causes drop in performance for simple tasks like bus balance, catapult. However, they is crucial for better exploration later on for more complex tasks. Code-as-Policy is deterministic, so perfectly places the block at center of catapult, getting only one of three goals. Introducing the sampling-based planners by themselves also not enough, you need retrying. Key thing to note here, is that learning retrying behavior always helps.

Policy Ablations

Key differences between BCZero and Diffusion is action generation. DDPM Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models v.s Huber Loss on MLP. Action representation (Abs or Delta), Both predict a sequence, and how much in that sequence is used. Why execution horizon matters so much? Because diverse action sequence it learns from means that actions can be jittery if too short, drop objects. A sequence prediction tends to be more continuous. BCZero, spatial softmax bottlenecks visual representation too much for multi-task. Here, it can still work.

Language Model Ablations

Tuned for GPT3, but suspect Llama 13B should also be sufficient, if not 70B. Modularized prompts allows a lot of ease of prompt tuning.

Error Analysis

As long as its diverse, and successful some of the time, its sufficient. Higher success rate, then more data generation efficiency. Note, what success rate doesn't capture are other qualitative notions of good data, like retrying behavior, which are also very important for downstream performance.
